Also, " That misers blamed money.
but were preposterously fond of it."
He often condemned those who praise the just for being superior to money, but who at the same time are eager themselves for great riches.
He was also very indignant at seeing men sacrifice to the Gods to procure good health, and yet at the sacrifice eating in a manner injurious to health.
He often expressed his surprise at slaves, who, seeing their masters eating in a gluttonous manner, still do not themselves lay hands on any of the eatables.
He would frequently praise those who were about to marry, and yet did not marry ;
or who were about to take a voyage, and yet did not take a voyage;
or who were about to engage in affairs of state, and did not do so;
and those who were about to rear children, yet did not rear any;
and those who were preparing to take up their abode with princes, and yet did not take it up.
